{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17527210","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17527210"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:29:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:29:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14193"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14193","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14193"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.33,0.03,0.13,0,0.5]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6876"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55564"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6876","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6876"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14193"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41104"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1881"},{"type":"tags","id":"2355"},{"type":"tags","id":"4916"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4978"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15658"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55564","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55564"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic seeking help for her heroin use. She reports using heroin daily for the past three years and has attempted to quit several times without success. She experiences intense cravings, uses increasing amounts to achieve the desired effect, and suffers from withdrawal symptoms when she tries to stop. Her heroin use has led to problems at work and strained relationships with family members. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She works part-time as a waitress and lives with her partner, who is supportive of her seeking treatment.  On examination, she appears anxious but otherwise well. Her pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 120/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. There are old track marks visible on her arms, but no signs of current infection.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first-line pharmacological treatment for this patient\u0027s opioid dependence?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Methadone","Diazepam","Naltrexone","Lofexidine","Buprenorphine-naloxone"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn the management of opioid dependence, \u003Cstrong\u003Ebuprenorphine-naloxone\u003C/strong\u003E is considered the first-line pharmacological treatment in Australia. This combination medication is preferred due to its improved safety profile and reduced risk of diversion compared to other options.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMethadone\u003C/strong\u003E is also an effective treatment for opioid dependence and has been used for many years. However, it is generally considered second-line due to its higher risk of overdose, especially during the induction phase, and greater potential for diversion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENaltrexone\u003C/strong\u003E is an opioid antagonist used in relapse prevention for opioid dependence. However, it requires complete detoxification before initiation and has lower retention rates compared to agonist treatments like buprenorphine or methadone. It is not typically used as a first-line treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiazepam\u003C/strong\u003E, a benzodiazepine, may be used to manage some withdrawal symptoms during detoxification but is not a primary treatment for opioid dependence. Long-term use of benzodiazepines in patients with substance use disorders is generally avoided due to the risk of dependence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELofexidine\u003C/strong\u003E is an alpha-2 adrenergic agonist that can be used to manage opioid withdrawal symptoms. While it can be helpful in the detoxification process, it is not a maintenance treatment for opioid dependence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that pharmacological treatment should always be combined with psychosocial interventions, such as counselling and support groups. Additionally, harm reduction strategies like needle exchange programs should be implemented to prevent complications such as HIV and hepatitis C. The choice of treatment should be individualised based on the patient\u0027s preferences, circumstances, and treatment history.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Buprenorphine-naloxone is the first-line pharmacotherapy for opioid dependence in Australia due to its safety profile and reduced risk of diversion.","Psychosocial interventions, including counselling and support groups, are essential components of opioid dependence treatment.","Harm reduction strategies, such as needle exchange programs, are important in managing opioid dependence to prevent complications like HIV and hepatitis C."],"references":["Frei M. Opioid dependence-management in general practice. Australian family physician. 2010 Aug;39(8):548-52. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/812cb17b-0b98-42e9-bfb2-dba2277bb559/Opioid-dependence-management-in-general-practice.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41104"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14193"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":